      {
        "type": "email",
        "html": "<p>Hello {first_name, \"there\"},</p><p>I hope your week has started well. This is being written from the midst of the chaos of home-schooling, as one daughter works on her teacher-set English, and the other works through today's Oak National Academy lessons. My decision a year ago to buy both my daughters iPads never seemed more prescient‚Ä¶</p><p>I'm hoping for a busy week on the blog, despite being on homeschooling duty while my wife drives towards a marking deadline. Keep your eye out for something important in the morning‚Ä¶</p>"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Facebook: doesn't care about news",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h2",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "This is your periodic reminder that we ‚Äî still ‚Äî need Facebook far more than Zuckerberg's empire needs news. It's been quite clear about that for years, and this message reinforces that. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The percentage of most people's newsfeeds that is made up of national news stories is really quite small. And people would keep coming back to the site, even if that went to zero. Most people are on the app to connect with friends, family and neighbours, not read news stories.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "This, if nothing else, should be a stark reminder of why we need to develop direct reader engagement strategies, not mediated ones. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "bookmark",
        "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/jun/15/facebook-says-it-doesnt-need-news-stories-for-its-business-and-wont-pay-to-share-them-in-australia",
        "metadata": {
          "url": "http://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/jun/15/facebook-says-it-doesnt-need-news-stories-for-its-business-and-wont-pay-to-share-them-in-australia",
          "title": "Facebook says it doesn‚Äôt need news stories for its business and won‚Äôt pay to share them in Australia",
          "description": "Social media giant rejects ACCC proposal, saying it could cut out news completely without any significant impact on its business",
          "author": "Naaman Zhou",
          "publisher": "The Guardian",
          "thumbnail": "https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a230402871691d205dd874b7fab00fe1e2bf9d1e/0_65_3500_2099/master/3500.jpg?width=1200&height=630&quality=85&auto=format&fit=crop&overlay-align=bottom%2Cleft&overlay-width=100p&overlay-base64=L2ltZy9zdGF0aWMvb3ZlcmxheXMvdGctZGVmYXVsdC5wbmc&enable=upscale&s=23e7cd75ddcd250b6bf6e3b44f3320bd",
          "icon": "https://static.guim.co.uk/images/favicon-32x32.ico"
        }
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Meshing the language of news and conspiracy theories",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "For years, we've used a distinct formula of news package as a shorthand for authority, particualrly in broadcast journalism. Couple that forumla with the psychological appeal of conspiracy theories - the sense that you are an insider because you \"get\" the \"secret\" the \"sheeple\" can't see‚Ä¶ well, it's a toxic brew. And, as this article makes plain, the internet and the advance in digital recording technology has facilitated this. Anyone can shoot near-professional quality video in the familiar languge of news. And people are drawn in by it. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "How do we counter this? If nothing else, this should be a stark reminder of why we need to develop direct reader engagement strategies, not mediated ones.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
